INSERT INTO `writing` VALUES (1,1,'1','Ella is on the run - from the law. She goes to find refuge with her cousin Rita who offers her a place to stay for as long as she needs.','On the Run','2015-12-11 20:05:35','2016-03-10 10:41:19','There were eighteen vertical stripes spanning across each seat of the greyhound bus. Five orange, three yellow, five blue, three red and two grey. Ella had been staring at the stripes on the seat in front of her for the last hour or so as the bus steadily made its way further and further north into the mountains. She closed her eyes, trying to recite the order of the stripes from memory: yellow, red, blue, orange, grey, orange, blue... But as she did, visions of her husband suddenly entered her mind\'s eye - his usually calm, handsome face became vicious and ugly as it contorted with rage, his mouth spitting accusations out at her as the flat of his hand darted towards her face - the vision seemed so real to her that she involuntarily jerked her head away, as if to escape his slap.\r\n\r\nShe opened her eyes, abandoning the stripes and instead staring at the shadows of the trees outside as they passed by the window. Surely she was close to Natchika now - she\'d already been travelling for several hours, suffering the damp, mouldy odour of soiled upholstery, the faint sounds of unrecognisable music and the rather questionable suspension of the vehicle which became all too noticeable when it ran over potholes and rounded corners.\r\n\r\nThe mountains were a far cry from her home on the beach, and leaving it hadn\'t been easy for her - she loved her house more than anything. She hated having to leave most of her possessions behind, having to pack lean and mean and cram what she had hurriedly chosen into one meagre suitcase. But it had to be done. The alternative course of action didn\'t bear thinking about.\r\n\r\nThe driver slowed the bus down as he turned the next corner. The bus rumbled to a slow stop beside a brightly lit roadside diner. The driver glanced at Ella through his rearview mirror and called out, \"This is Natchika, ma\'am.\"\r\n\r\nThe temperature outside the bus was crisp and so cold that her breaths come out in little puffs of steam in front of her face. The air here, Ella noted, was thick and heavy with the perfume of the surrounding mountain forests. She stood still, allowing herself to enjoy it for a moment. Then she began the arduous task of dragging her luggage into the diner where she took a seat at the counter near the back. She chose that spot because it afforded her a good view of the front doors. She might be sleep deprived and worried out of her mind but no one was going to catch her by surprise if she could help it.\r\n\r\nThe waitress poured her a coffee and asked if she wanted anything else. Ella distractedly shook her head. She was preoccupied with the television set sat high up on a shelf behind the bar. She noted that it was playing reruns of \'I dream of Genie\'. Would the waitress notice if a news report featuring a photo of Ella suddenly flashed up on the screen right then? Would Ella even be recognisable after all the pains she\'d taken to disguise herself?\r\n\r\nShe stared solemnly into the still, dark pool of coffee she hadn\'t touched yet as the bells above the door to the diner jangled a cheerful yet jarring alarm. Ella\'s head shot up as she looked towards the door. A bolt of fear struck at her chest. She watched as two men entered, and sighed with relief - it was just some locals  particularly attractive ones, too, she noted.\r\n\r\nThey took seats at the counter also, but directly opposite from her. While they were both strikingly handsome, one in particular caught her eye. He was tall and lean but also muscular, and his physique made her think that he either worked out at the gym all the time or had a very physically demanding job. He had light sandy coloured hair that was cut very short, and high, flat cheekbones, with a jaw-line that angled down perfectly towards a round, cleft chin. His eyes were the silvery green-blue of a tumultuous ocean on an overcast day and a smattering of salt and pepper coloured regrowth was beginning to spread its way up his cheeks.\r\n\r\nElla was taken aback by how handsome the man was, and when he caught her staring at him, she was so embarrassed that he had caught her openly gaping at him that she almost blushed before hurriedly averting her gaze. He was movie star handsome, that was for sure, but what was he doing all the way out in Natchika? Surely he should be off in Hollywood somewhere trying to make a name for himself, not in some sleepy mountainside town that only had a lumber mill going for it.\r\n\r\nAs Ella got over her shame she peered sideways through her hair at the pair, and noticed that the other man was staring at her now, too. He was slightly shorter than first one, not quite as lean but still solidly built, and where the first man was fair, this one was dark  black hair, dark brown, almost black eyes, and a deep olive complexion. He either worked out all the time at the same gym as the first guy, or else they both had physically demanding jobs at the same place. \r\n\r\nThe first guy stopped looking at her and took out a menu. Ella didn\'t dare look directly at him again for fear that he would catch her staring. Instead she returned to contemplating the coffee she couldn\'t quite bring herself to drink.\r\n\r\n\"She\'s probably here for the job at the Sheriff\'s office,\" Danny said. He flashed one of his warmest smiles her way, but she wouldn\'t lift her head to meet his gaze, so he quickly gave up.\r\n\r\nHunter, while under the guise of inspecting his menu, took this opportunity to scrutinise the woman seated at the counter more closely. Despite the bags under her eyes and the anxiety evident in her face, he could tell she was beautiful.\r\n\r\nShe was staring into her cup of coffee and distractedly tapping her fingers on the counter top. She seemed completely lost in thought; that is, until some slightly startling little noise disturbed her contemplations  a fork dropping, someone coughing, a truck driving past  then her body would momentarily tense and she would dart an accusing glance at the offending sound until she had convinced herself it wasn\'t a threat.\r\n\r\nHis eyes caught sight of the suitcase resting against the counter at her feet. Its zipper wasn\'t zipped the whole way round and bits of cloth were peeking out of the top of it the way handkerchiefs poke out of a suit pockets. He supposed that this woman, whoever she was, had left her home on the spur of the moment, trying to squeeze as much as she could into it, not stopping long enough to bother to make sure it was properly closed.\r\n\r\nAs his eyes moved from her suitcase to her legs he found himself checking out her body. She was very lithe, probably either a dancer or a marathon runner, he guessed. She had very high, firm looking breasts and a tiny little waist set above long, elegant legs. Her hair was very stylishly cut in a rather severe bob, and it was the colour of midnight. Her eyes, as he remembered from catching her gaze, were soft, warm and a chocolate brown colour.\r\n\r\nHe said to Danny, \"I don\'t think so. I think she\'s probably just passing through.\"\r\nDanny shrugged. \"If you say so.\" He made his usual breakfast order to the waitress.\r\n\r\nElla knew the good looking sandy haired man seated at the counter across from her had been staring at her, and she felt uneasy about it. Had he seen a television report about her before coming to the diner this morning? Had he recognised her face from somewhere? Again her eyes darted up to the television set. It was still playing \'I dream of Genie.\'\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, she realised, she culd just be paranoid; the man could simply have been checking her out. She had been, after all, known to turn heads every once in a while. It was probably lack of sleep that was wearing her down, making her wrongly assume that everyone she had come into contact with since leaving knew exactly who she was and what she was running from.\r\n\r\nReally, there was only one way for her to find out exactly why the gorgeous guy on the other side of the room had been staring at her. She gulped and then turned her head to look over at him shyly.\r\n\r\nHis eyes were hard to read; they were expressionless, as were his perfectly chiseled features. They gave absolutely nothing away. Those lovely azure coloured eyes of his bore into hers with a puzzling intensity she couldn\'t understand, his mouth and chin completely unmoving, his long, slender fingers fiddling idly with the menu in front of him.\r\n\r\nElla inhaled sharply as she felt a pleasant sort of thrill shoot down into her lower region. Not knowing why this man was staring so intently at her was actually kind of exciting... What she did know, though, was that the tell-tale signs of recognition were not apparent on his gorgeous face. He probably had no idea she was on the run from the law. She allowed herself to breathe a sigh of relief.\r\n\r\nHe continued to stare at her brazenly, not once looking away. His features softened somewhat, and his expression looked more contemplative now, and he tilted his head ever so slightly to one side and narrowed his eyes just a tiny bit. One corner of his mouth lifted by the teeniest amount. It was almost as if he was asking her a question...\r\n\r\nShe felt the stirrings of desire inside of her, rising up through the core of her body, like a deeply sleeping snake that had suddenly been prodded awake, warming up her stomach, her chest, her neck and her cheeks as it uncoiled within her. If she wasn\'t in so much trouble, the answer to his question would have been a resounding yes, yes, yes!\r\n\r\nBut she was in trouble, and she certainly didn\'t need any more of it. So she forced herself to break away from his stare. As she did so, she thought she could hear a soft chuckle  but when she looked up again, he was intently reading the menu, then talking to the waitress.\r\n\r\n\"What was that about?\" Danny asked, his eyes darting from Hunter to Ella, then back again. He tried to catch her gaze but she wouldn\'t lift it from where it had landed, back to the contents of her coffee cup. He was slightly disappointed. And jealous.\r\n\r\nHunter simply smiled to himself. Even if she was just passing through, he doubted she would forget him too quickly. He knew he wouldn\'t forget her too soon, anyway.\r\n\r\n\"Don\'t worry, they\'re harmless.\" The waitress smiled at Ella. She must have noticed the attention the two men had been giving her. \"We don\'t get too many new people around here.\" She went to refill Ella\'s coffee and stopped when she realised Ella hadn\'t sipped a drop. Ella looked up at her and smiled. \"I\'m not worried.\"\r\nThe waitress frowned. \"Something wrong with the coffee? Want me to pour you some from a new batch?\"\r\n\"No, it\'s fine, I\'m just...\"\r\n\"Lost in thought?\" The waitress smiled reassuringly at Ella\'s apprehensive expression. Again she felt herself in the grip of paranoia. She stole another nervous glance up at the TV set. She nodded.\r\n\"I can turn that off if it bothers you,\" the waitress told her. \"No one really watches it.\"\r\nElla shook her head. She would rather see the report come up, if it did, than not know about it at all. \"Perhaps if you could just change the channel? To some news, maybe?\"\r\n\"Sure thing.\"\r\n\"Thanks.\"\r\n\r\nHunter watched Ella as inconspicuously as he could while she stared nervously up at the TV. His attention was again drawn to the heavy bags she had with her. He concluded that she was too old to be a runaway, and definitely too hygienic looking to be homeless, and considering the fact that Natchika wasn\'t really on the way to anywhere special, she probably wasn\'t stopped there on a layover. She must have meant to stop at Natchika, he decided, despite the fact that there wasn\'t much there  just a small strip of shops, a tiny minimart, a liquor store, a post office, the antiques shop, a gas station and the all night diner out on the highway. The town\'s tiny population was mainly comprised of people who worked at the lumber mill fifteen miles out of town in Narrow Rapids. The place really had no other reason to exist.\r\n\r\n\"She\'s running from something,\" Hunter told Danny quietly. \"She\'s got a hunted look about her.\"\r\nDanny shook his head in disbelief. \"You\'re just imagining things. I\'ll bet you fifty bucks she\'s headed to Beattie\'s Cove to take the job cleaning the Sheriff\'s Office.\"\r\n\"We\'ll see,\" Hunter replied, not convinced.\r\n\r\nHunter and Danny continued to eat their food while Ella\'s gaze remained transfixed by the TV screen. So mesmerised she was, so absorbed in her task of watching every single report to make sure it didn\'t feature her, that she almost didn\'t notice as the two men paid their bill and got up to leave. As the bell above the door jangled, she couldn\'t stop herself from stealing a quick glance towards them  although she probably wouldn\'t admit it to herself, she desperately wanted to see the cute blonde man one last time. As the glass door swung shut behind him he turned his head to look back at her one last time also. She could almost feel her heart skip a beat. Realising that she\'d probably never see this man again, Ella then chose to do something uncharacteristically brave - well, brave for her, at least  she winked at him.\r\n\r\nImmediately after performing this feat of confidence, her body betrayed her in an act of pure deceit  it caused her face to quickly flush with colour and her breathing to became rapid. Her hands, safely hidden in her lap, trembled slightly. She could hardly believe she had the gall to do what she had just done! And how would the man react, anyway? She almost couldn\'t look.\r\n\r\nHunter, however, just laughed, smiling appreciatively at her. She breathed a sigh of relief. He nodded a goodbye at her and then turned around, and then he and his friend put their helmets on and got on their motorbikes. A moment later they had driven off, the loud, rumbling sounds of their bikes slowly receding into the distance.\r\n\r\nAs the sun began to brighten up the day outside, Ella began to see a breathtaking view of the mountains in the far off distance through the diner windows. The sight calmed her somewhat; those large, looming shadowy mountains combined with the tall, green forests nearby made her feel small and well hidden, which was exactly how she wanted to feel right now.\r\n\r\nShe looked at her watch: eight a.m. Was it too early to call Rita?\r\n\r\nElla went to stand inside the phone booth just outside the diner. As she fed it coins and dialed Rita\'s number her stomach began to feel as though it was doing flip flops. It was silly - Rita would be warm and welcoming, as she always was, despite the fact that the two of them had not spoken for three years. Ella was sure she was worrying over nothing. \r\n\r\nHer and her cousin had always been very close. They were surrogate sisters  Ella was an only child and Rita had only had brothers and no sisters, and despite the three years between their ages, the girls had spent their youth playing together outdoors. They climbed trees and rolled down hillsides, picked flowers and tormented insects, built forts and started water fights, all the way up until their tomboy days suddenly ended and the stunningly beautiful Rita began turning heads wherever they went.\r\n\r\nAfter that the girls still played outdoors, running through the tall grasses and trees, but now whilst also being pursued by boys...\r\n\r\nThe phone rang three times before someone picked up.\r\n\"Hello?\" It was Mike, Rita\'s husband. They hadn\'t met yet, but Rita had told Ella all about him the last time they had seen each other.\r\n\"Hey,\" Ella said, her nerves getting to her and her voice wavering. \"It\'s Ella here. I\'m Rita\'s cousin. Is she available to talk?\"\r\n\"Sure,\" Mike grumbled. \"Let me just go get her.\"\r\n\"Thanks,\" Ella replied. Before he put the phone down he said, \"It\'s pretty early to be calling, you know. But I\'ll go get her.\"\r\n\r\nElla silently chided herself for not leaving the call until later. She listened intently to the noises on the other end of the line  thumping, Mike\'s booming voice calling out to Rita, more thumping, a door slamming shut, the revs of a motorbike roaring to life, and then finally Rita\'s voice as she picked up the phone.\r\n\"Ella?\"\r\n\"Rita,\" Ella replied, her eyes filling with tears at the sound of her beloved cousin\'s voice. \"You have no idea how good it is to hear your voice again!\"\r\nRita laughed warmly. \"Ella Bella! How long has it been?\"\r\n\"A few years...\"\r\n\"Wow, time really flies! I can\'t believe it\'s been that long since I left Safety Valley.\"\r\n\r\nElla went silent as her mind sprang back to the home she had left in Safety Valley. She found herself thinking back to the situation she was fleeing from.\r\n\"Ella?\" Rita sounded concerned. \"Is everything okay?\"\r\n\"Oh, Rita...\"\r\n\"What\'s wrong?\" The tone of Rita\'s voice had completely switched now from jovial to serious. \"What happened?\"\r\n\"Oh, nothing too bad,\" Ella lied, the tears flowing freely now. She quickly switched the subject in an effort to distract herself enough to stop the tears. \"Actually, I\'m in town.\"\r\n\"Holy cow! Where are you? I\'ll throw something on and come and get you.\"\r\nElla wavered. She thought of Mike  how his voice had sounded. \"It\'s pretty early,\" Ella said. \"I don\'t want to be too much of an inconvenience to you guys.\"\r\n\"Nonsense,\" Rita replied. \"Mike\'s just gone to work and I\'m up now. Where are you?\"\r\nRelief washed through Ella. \"I\'m at the all night diner on the highway. Thanks Rita. I really appreciate this. I can\'t wait to see you.\"\r\n\"Me either. I\'ll be there in five, okay?\"\r\n\r\nElla watched as Rita parked her old yellow hatchback out the front of the diner. She was already outside with her oversized duffle bags in tow. When Rita laid eyes on Ella again for the first time in three years, she noticed a few subtle changes that had taken place in her cousin\'s appearance. Her hair, which had flowed down in golden brown waves to her waist, was now dyed blue-black and cut in a severe, straight bob that flatteringly framed her jawline. It shone in the morning sun with all the gloss of a high fashion magazine.\r\n\r\nElla\'s frame was more delicate than Rita remembered, too - not that Ella had ever been a big girl, but she had inherited the Connor family curves along with Rita. Now she could easily be mistaken for one of the models in one of those fashion magazines.\r\n\r\nElla thought Rita looked just as she had remembered - her beautiful long, red hair was still as shiny and thick as ever and she still had that stunning hourglass figure that drove men wild. Ella had been jealous of that figure growing up and all the attention Rita had garnered from it, but now she was happy enough with her own body - she had taken up running several times a week, and was satisfied with her own long, lean runner\'s frame.\r\n\r\nAs Rita got out of the car, the two of them immediately broke out into smiles at the sight of each other and almost ran into each other as they went in for a hug. They embraced for several moments, and Ella felt as if a weight had been lifted off of her shoulders for the first time in hours. Rita pulled back and held onto Ella by her shoulders. \"You haven\'t changed a bit!\"\r\n\"You haven\'t either,\" Ella replied. \"Just as gorgeous as ever!\"\r\nRita regarded Ella with concern. \"Let\'s get you back to my place and get some coffee into you! Did you sleep last night?\"\r\n\r\nWhen they got to Rita\'s, Ella was impressed by how beautiful the surrounding scenery of the mountain forest was. They had driven up the mountainside on a road that wound around to the east. Rita had turned into a driveway that extended in a fair way from the road. When they finally reached the end of it, Ella saw the house itself - a long, white weatherboard, probably built in the fifties, was surrounded on all sides by dense forest. Its paint was peeling and its roof was wearing out in spots.\r\n\r\nRita parked in a small clearing at the side of the house. As Ella got out of the car the fresh mountain air hit her with full force. She breathed in its dewy freshness, then looked up. The tall trees reached towards the sky with their long, arm-like branches. Ella once again felt hidden and safe. She looked back at the house.\r\n\r\nTo one side of the house was a caravan, and around the back there was a camper van, and both looked very lived in. To the right of the camper van was a large shed. Ella looked questioningly at Rita.\r\n\r\n\"Hunter lives in the caravan and Danny lives in the camper van. Hunter\'s sister, Sara, lives in the house with us.\"\r\nElla blinked. Rita explained, \"Friends of ours who are staying with us. Wonderful people. You\'ll love them.\"\r\nElla asked uncertainly, \"And all of you live here... Together?\"\r\nRita nodded. \"One big happy family!\"\r\n\"Is there room in there for me?\"\r\n\"We actually do have a spare room for you, luckily enough. Come inside, I\'ll show you.\"\r\n\r\nThe inside of the house was very cosy and more than a little messy with books, magazines, motorcycle parts, makeup, clothes and other things strewn all over the place. Ella dumped her bags on the large old corner settee and took a seat at the kitchen counter. Rita put the kettle on and leaned on the counter across from Ella. \"Well, Ella Bella, not that I\'m not happy to see you, because believe me, I am; but I know you didn\'t come all this way just to catch up with me. So spill it - what\'s going on?\"\r\n\r\nElla took a deep breath. Her stomach started grinding once again as images flashed through her head from the past few days. She tried to decide just how much she should tell her cousin about her current situation. As she thought about what must be happening back at home now, she began to wonder just how big of a mess she had gotten herself into. Was dragging Rita into this mess along with her the right thing to do?\r\n\r\n\"Sam and I are having problems,\" Ella said. She laughed inwardly  she was so grossly under exaggerating that it was comical. Rita nodded sympathetically. \"I\'m so sorry to hear that.\"\r\n\"I just needed some time away from him... I\'m sorry I didn\'t call first. I really just wanted to get away as quickly as I could.\"\r\n\"Oh, that\'s okay. You\'re like a sister to me  you\'re welcome here whenever you want and you can stay for as long as you need.\"\r\n\r\nRita smiled sweetly at Ella. Ella returned the smile, a pang of guilt stabbing at her stomach. While she was relieved that her cousin believed her cover story, she felt terribly bad about lying to her, but she wasn\'t anywhere near ready to tell her the truth yet.\r\n\r\n\"You\'re like the only relative I have right now that will actually talk to me,\" Rita joked.\r\n\"You haven\'t spoken to your parents in three years?\"\r\n\"Actually, they haven\'t spoken to me. Not since Mike and I eloped.\" Rita showed Ella her lovely wedding ring. Ella gushed. \"It\'s beautiful! I just wish I could have been there.\"\r\n\"No, you don\'t,\" Rita said. \"It was just us and a few friends at the courthouse over at Beattie\'s Cove. We signed the documents, the judge pronounced us man and wife and that was it. We went and played pool afterwards. It was nothing like the wedding you and Sam put on.\"\r\n\r\nElla remembered back to her expensive, lavish wedding. Three hundred guests, a swing band, her ridiculously expensive strapless wedding dress and all those delicate pink peonies everywhere... She said a little sadly, \"It just goes to show, the wedding isn\'t really much of an indicator as to how good the marriage will turn out.\"\r\n\"I really am sorry to hear things aren\'t going well... Is there no way you can reconcile?\"\r\n\r\nElla was definitely a hundred percent sure that there was no way her and Sam could ever possibly reconcile, especially not after what she had done to him...\r\n\r\n\"I\'m afraid not,\" she told her cousin. Her cousin rounded the bench and gave her a big, warm hug. After they separated from the embrace, Rita said, \"I guess you\'d be a bit tired after all those hours you traveled on a bus to get here. Feel free to sleep for a while.\"\r\n\"Thanks,\" Ella said. \"I think I do need a nap actually.\"\r\n\r\nRita stood up and took one of Ella\'s bags. \"Come and see your new room.\" Ella grabbed the other bag and followed her. As Ella dropped her bag on the floor and sat on the bed in her new room a wave of fatigue overcame her. She yawned and stretched extravagantly.\r\n\r\nAdding some words to create a writing log.\r\n\r\n\"Sleep tight,\" Rita said, leaving the room and shutting the door behind her. And before Ella could think of a reason not to take a nap, she fell asleep.',4405,'chapter'),(2,1,'2','Ella meets the gang and settles in, but can she manage to keep her secret from everyone?','First Meetings','2015-12-17 14:30:05','2016-02-05 06:05:46','When Ella awoke later, she went out to the kitchen to find Rita, but Rita wasn\'t there; however, she had thoughtfully left a note for Ella on the counter: \r\n\r\nElla, \r\nHad to go do a four-hour shift at the grocery store. Be back at 6. Make yourself right at home. \r\nLove & Hugs, \r\nRita \r\n\r\nThe house was eerily quiet owing to its secluded location - there were no sounds of traffic, no dogs barking nearby, no neighbours talking outside - and the massive shroud of trees that surrounded the place blocked out most of the sunlight which made it rather dark and deary inside. Ella felt very alone. She shivered involuntarily. \r\n\r\nShe forced herself out of contemplation mode and into productive mode. First and foremost, she really needed to take a shower. Three days on the run without access to a bathroom had left her feeling grimy and gross. Her hair was limp from excess oil build up and her nails were starting to accumulate dirt underneath them. She felt far from glamorous.\r\n\r\nShe stripped off and stepped into the shower. The water pressure was less than ideal and it took the hot water unit a fair few minutes to heat up. As she stood naked in the shower trying not to let the icy water touch her bare skin she listened with a certain amount of concern as the old water pipes rattled and shook. Ella thought then of her own bathroom, her own modern house back at Safety Valley. There, she could always make out the sounds of traffic and people talking nearby, and the shower always had a tank of hot water ready. She felt a sudden intense pang of homesickness. It was very silent out here, and very cold. Nothing like her home by the beach at all. \r\n\r\nThen she remembered what had happened between her and Sam, and the homesickness was replaced with fear, guilt and shame.\r\n\r\nAfter getting out of the shower and drying herself off, she got dressed, putting on some tight black jeans and her favourite t-shirt. She applied some make-up, dried her hair and put it up, and began to feel vaguely human again. She made herself a coffee out in the kitchen and sat down on the couch. And promptly started to grow very anxious. \r\n\r\nShe felt out of place. Right now she should be at work making photocopies, filing, answering the phone. Instead she was here, sitting on this old threadbare couch in this dark, dreary house, nothing to occupy her and thoughts of the police busting in suddenly to arrest her haunting her every breath. \r\n\r\nShe got up and went outside. Rita wasn\'t there to talk to and distract her from her thoughts, so she decided to do the only thing she could think of that might help her to get her mind off things a little - take a walk.\r\n\r\nThere was a very faint trailbike track leading into the thick of the forest. She followed it as it snaked downwards and to the left. Ferns and trees intoxicated her with their heady perfumes and birds talked to each other high up in the tops of trees as she passed by. It really was idyllic, and should have been peaceful. If only she could steer her mind away from herself and her troubles for enough time to enjoy it.\r\n\r\nEventually she came upon a gently babbling stream. The noises the water made as it rushed past rocks and down the hill were very soothing. Following it for a time led her deeper and deeper into the forest, which made her feel both safer and yet more isolated and alone all at once. \r\n\r\nShe wondered then how alone she would feel without Rita to talk to - if she did end up going her own way after staying here for a week or so. She would have nothing but her own thoughts to keep her company. She would have to fight hard to distract herself at every moment. \r\n\r\nShe turned around to slowly head back. She didn\'t want to stray too far from the house - she missed Rita already. She hoped her cousin would return soon. She had never felt quite so alone in her whole life since fleeing Safety Valley.  \r\n\r\nAs she reached the beginning of the track again, she could just make out the sounds of singing over the tinny music of a small portable radio. It was playing a Bruce Springsteen song - and Ella thought whomever was singing along to it was doing quite a good job. \r\n\r\n\"I get up in the evening, and I ain\'t got nothing to say. I come home in the morning, I go to bed feeling the same way.\" \r\n\r\nElla exited the forest and located the source of the singing - it was coming from the trailer at the side of the house. A man with short blonde hair stepped outside. He had his back to her so he couldn\'t see her standing there. Ella felt uncomfortable - she wondered if she should announce her presence in some way - a cough, maybe breaking some branches with her shoes. But as she was contemplating it, the man started to take his shirt off. \r\n\r\nShe watched as the muscles in his thick arms bulged into round, hard lumps as he pulled his shirt up over his head. She could see his back now. There was a nice little curved trail leading from his broad shoulder blades down to his lower back, and at his lower back, above his nicely shaped butt, were two dimples that winked playfully at her. He lopped the shirt inside the trailer. \r\n\r\nElla felt slightly ashamed of herself for admiring the well-built stranger in such a blatantly obvious way, but she decided that it was perfectly acceptable as long as he didn\'t spot her. Her eyes were riveted to him as he sat down on a crate and bent over to remove one of his boots. She could tell from this angle that his buttocks were very tight. \r\n\r\n\"Cant start a fire... Can\'t start a fire without a spark. This gun\'s for hire... Even if we\'re just dancing in the dark.\"\r\n\r\nHe pulled the other boot off and flung it into the trailer as well. Then he got up and undid the top button of his pants. He turned his body so that his side was facing Ella now. Her heart fluttered - she was conflicted - she wanted to stay there and continue to watch him undress, but there was the danger now that he might spot her. Her breaths came shallow and sharp - partly because she was excited at the prospect of being caught, and party because she was forcing herself to stay perfectly still, hoping that he wouldn\'t see her watching him out of the corner of his eye. \r\n\r\nHe unzipped the zipper of his pants and then pulled them down slowly over his hips. He was wearing tight dark grey trunks, and from that angle, Ella could see the profile of his package, and it certainly seemed like it would not disappoint. She also had a good view of his behind - it looked very firm and very perky. She felt a sudden urge to go over there and touch it just to make sure it was as firm as she believed it would be. \r\n\r\nThe man bent slightly and pulled one perfectly sculpted leg out of the jeans and then the other. Ella smiled to herself. This man was in really amazing physical condition. As he bent to finish getting out of the jeans, the six pack of his mid-section tightened slightly and his pectoral muscles bounced a little, so smooth and round they were that Ella wondered what they would feel like to touch with her hands, what they would feel like to lick with her tongue... Her eyes were then drawn downwards to his thighs and calves - they were so muscular, so firm... He flung the jeans into the trailer. \r\n\r\nHer breath caught in her throat as she realised there was only one item of clothing left for him to remove. Her hand went up to her lips unconsciously as she held her breath and waited for him to remove his trunks. \r\n\r\nSuddenly his head snapped around and he levelled his green-blue coloured eyes at her. His expression was slightly shocked, very serious - then, slowly, it softened. Ella felt her cheeks burning. Her mouth opened, but no words would come out. She was so incredibly embarrassed. She really should have said something earlier to let him know that she was standing there...\r\n\r\nA small smile tugged at one corner of the man\'s mouth. He was enjoying her embarrassment. As he stared at her questioningly he put his hands on his hips and stood a little taller. \"Like what you see?\"\r\nElla\'s mouth fell open even wider. \"I... I\'m so sorry...\" \r\n\r\nShe couldn\'t help but appreciate this new pose, though. Several different muscle groups were suddenly more visible. The man laughed, his smile wide now, and his hands dropped from his hips. \"No, really, did you enjoy the show?\"\r\nElla felt a sudden jolt of adrenalin course through her heart as she retorted, \"I really enjoyed the singing more than anything.\"\r\n\r\nThe man was now embarrassed himself. He laughed uncomfortably. He hadnt expected her to answer him back and he tended to keep his love of Bruce Springsteen strictly a secret, and his singing even more so. \r\n\r\nElla herself was shocked that she had managed such a smart-ass retort. As little as a week ago she wouldnt have been able to manage such a feat. She wondered where this new-found courage had come from. \r\n\r\nHunter realised just then that he had seen this woman before - it was the woman from the diner that morning. \"Hey... Didn\'t I see you in the diner this morning?\"\r\nShe tilted her head. She recognised him as well. He was one of the two men from the corner booth at the diner who had been watching her. \"Yes... I recognise you too. My name\'s Ella. I\'m Rita\'s cousin... I\'ll be staying here for a while.\" \r\n\"So you\'re not just some stranger then, out in the wilderness, spying on men while they get undressed.\" \r\nShe shook her head. Another surge of adrenalin coursed through her as she put her hands on her hips. \"You know, most men undress inside their houses...\"\r\n\r\nHe laughed and rubbed at his neck with one hand. He tended to do that whenever he was nervous. Ella thought it was endearing to see such a handsome man get so flustered  and realised with sudden pride that she had never actually managed to fluster one before. She beamed at him. \r\n\r\nHunter thought her smile was wonderful. It made her seem so open and inviting... So different from the haunted woman he had seen in the diner that morning. And he could get lost in those beautiful brown eyes... As he felt a slight stirring in his penis, he was suddenly acutely aware of his lack of clothing. Coughing uncomfortably, he said, \"Well, Ella, I\'m just going to go put some clothes back on now,\" and headed for the trailer door. Ella tried to force herself to look away as he entered the trailer but found that she just couldn\'t. She watched the back of his legs and his perky little buttocks as he climbed the tiny little trailer stairs in his underwear. \r\n\r\nHe called out to her while he was dressing, \"I could use a coffee right about now, what about you, Ella?\"\r\n\"Yes, another coffee certainly wouldn\'t hurt.\" She could hear noises coming from inside the trailer as he got ready  the opening and closing of cupboard doors and creaks coming from the floor of the trailer itself as he moved from one side of it to the other. She called out to him, Hey, I never caught your name?\r\n\r\nAs he came out of the trailer wearing jeans and a blue checked shirt, he answered, Hunter. He gestured for her to lead the way into the house. \r\n\r\nInside he put the kettle on and asked her how she took her coffee. \"White with one, thanks,\" she replied. When he had made the coffees they sat down on the settee. Her heart fluttered when he sat down no more than a foot away from her. She could smell his aftershave, his deoderant and even a bit of his sweat. She found the combination oddly intoxicating. \r\n\r\n\"So, how long are you staying for?\"\r\nElla took a moment to answer. \"Oh, I don\'t know... A couple of weeks or so.\" She shrugged and looked down at her hands. \r\n\"Ahuh,\" Hunter replied. \"Rita never mentioned you were coming.\"\r\n\r\nElla started to fidget with the coffee cup in her hands, turning it round and round. Hunter remembered the way she had seemed at the diner - very nervous, on edge almost, and tired, like she\'d been travelling for some time. She appeared to him to have almost reverted back to that state now. The playful, flirty woman who had been perving on him outside just before had all but vanished, replaced with this nervous, fidgeting woman who seemed preoccupied with something very pressing. \r\n\r\n\"Where are you from, anyway?\"\r\nElla laughed nervously. \"What is this, twenty questions?\"\r\nHunter was slightly taken aback. He desperately wanted to know what was troubling her but it seemed that she wasn\'t going to trust him  not yet, at least. \"No, not at all. I\'m sorry if I\'m being intrusive.\" \r\n\r\nElla looked over at him. He seemed genuine enough. His gorgeous eyes were locked with hers and she could see that he was wondering about her, that he could sense there was something bothering her. His concern for her, while intrusive and unwanted, also made her feel something else; something deep inside, something she hadn\'t felt in a long, long time. She chose to ignore it. It was a dangerous feeling. It was a feeling that lead to even more feelings and then vulnerability and finally betrayal as the man you thought you knew so well turned into someone entirely different and you couldn\'t understand when or how it had happened. \r\n \r\n\"It\'s okay. I\'m from back west. On the coast. And you? How long have you been staying with Rita and Mike?\"\r\nHunter recognised the deflection for what it was. She obviously wasn\'t going to give too much away and he accepted that. He wasn\'t going to press it any further - he wasn\'t the forceful type. \r\n\"From south of here. Been in this place about twelve months now. It\'s not such a bad place once you get used to it.\"\r\n\r\nHe could smell her from where he sat - her shampoo, which smelled like apples and cinnamon, and something else - the soap she used, maybe. Something sweet and musky. He liked how smooth her skin looked, how pale... He wanted to reach out and touch it, stroke it, see how she reacted to him and take her by surprise when she least expected it by putting his arm around her waist, drawing her to him and kissing her hard on the lips. He looked at her body... He thought it was magnificent, just the kind he liked - athletic and toned, like she worked out a lot, but not too much. He could see the toned curve of her butt through her jeans as she leaned over to put down her coffee, and her firm, round breasts through her t-shirt as she straighted up again. \r\n\r\nShe made him feel things he hadn\'t felt for a long time. In the twelve months he had been in Natchika he hadn\'t met someone as intriguing as her. She had it all - she was beautiful, with a smoking hot body, and humble - she seemed a little shy, a little taken aback by his attentions. He liked that about her. Also that she had a sense of humour. He was used to dealing with women who thought they were God\'s gift and he was over it. He wanted someone with a brain and a personality as well as looks for a change. He gave her a warm smile which she reciprocated. He felt a warmth spread through his chest and down to the pit of his stomach. And then...\r\n\r\nShe picked her coffee cup up again and took a sip from it, and that\'s when he spotted her wedding ring. He felt a wave of disappointment wash through him. The first woman he had met in a long time who actually ticked all of his boxes and she was married. Completely off-limits. He rubbed at his eyes with his fingers. He almost couldn\'t believe how unlucky he was.\r\n\r\nShe started to play with the ring absent-mindedly, twisting it round on her finger with her thumb. She carried on the conversation with him, unaware that he felt like he had crashed to the ground after soaring so high in the sky amongst the clouds. \"Where were you twelve months ago?\"\r\nHunter picked his coffee up and took a sip. His expression grew distant and he was silent for a moment before answering. \"My sister and I used to live in a place called Harmer, about five hundred miles south of here.\" \r\nElla was curious to know more about his past, about why he and his sister had decided to live with Mike and Rita, but she didn\'t want to pry. He suddenly seemed so cold, so closed off... She looked at him but he wouldn\'t meet her gaze anymore. \r\n\r\nShe desperately wanted to lift the tone again, to have him smile at her once more. \r\n\"So... You\'re a closet Bruce Springsteen fan, hey? How come? There\'s nothing wrong with liking the boss.\"\r\nHe smiled at her again, but it was different. It wasn\'t cheeky and playful as it had been before; instead it was polite, almost stand-offish, even. \r\n\"If Danny knew, I\'d never hear the end of it.\"\r\n\"Danny?\"\r\n\"Yeah, he lives here too. In the camper van round the other side of the house. When we first got here we drew straws - I wanted the camper van - the bed is more comfortable and it\'s about five degrees warmer inside. But I drew the short straw.\" \r\n\"Why not a room in the house?\"\r\nHunter shrugged. \"I like my privacy. I lived in a house with my sister for most of my life - I\'m over it.\" \r\n\r\nHe laughed suddenly and Ella was caught up by it, almost infected with it. He was showing her warmth again and it felt wonderful. She stared into his green-blue eyes, admired the way they crinkled at the edges, drawing her into them. Suddenly she felt a burning desire to be held by those strong, muscular arms of his - to be encircled and protected by them. She knew she shouldn\'t think such things about a man she hardly knew but she didn\'t care; she wanted to know what it would feel like to sink into his embrace, to feel the warmth of his chest, the beating of his heart - to be with a man who didn\'t feel the need to dominate her with force; rather, to be with one who would overpower her with tenderness. \r\n\r\nLikewise, with her staring into his eyes he found it incredibly difficult not to just reach out and touch her face, to not just draw her to him, put his hands through her hair and kiss her full, pouting lips. He wanted her, had done since the moment he had seen her in the diner that morning. But it wouldn\'t do. She was taken. \r\n\r\nHe cleared his throat and looked away. She was a married woman. He felt somehow wrong sitting there alone in the house with her. \"Speaking of Danny... He\'s in his camper van. You should meet him. I\'ll introduce you.\" Before she could answer, he got up and walked out the front door. She followed, wondering what had happened. He had seemed so warm just a moment ago; they had been so comfortable with one another. Now it almost felt like he didn\'t want to be alone with her. \r\n\r\nOutside they went round the back of the house to find the camper van. Hunter banged on the door three times. Yo Danny, he called out. \r\nYo Hunter, Danny replied from inside the van. What\'s up?\r\nSomeone out here you should meet.\r\n\r\nDanny opened the camper van door and peered out at them. His hair was dishevelled and he wasn\'t wearing a shirt. His eyes were sleepy as if he had just been awoken from a nap. When he spotted Ella he seemed to wake up all at once. He hadn\'t been expecting to see an attractive woman outside his door. \r\n\r\nElla again found herself in the enviable position of catching an extremely good looking guy half naked unawares. She hid her smirk behind her hand. Rather than retreat to put some clothes on like Hunter had, Danny stepped outside and gave Ella a big cheesy grin. Hey there... Didn\'t I see you in the diner this morning?\r\nElla nodded. Hunter introduced them like he had promised he would. This is Ella. Ella, this is Danny. Ella shook Danny\'s outstretched hand. Nice to meet you.\r\nDitto! Danny\'s enthusiasm was both obvious and infectious. Ella found herself grinning widely back at him. \r\nElla will be staying with us for a while, Hunter explained. She\'s Rita\'s cousin.\r\nOh, hey! That\'s great! Danny looked Ella up and down. He seemed to like what he saw. Ella laughed at how obvious he was. She hadn\'t met someone so brash before. Just then he pretended to brush something off his naked chest. Ella caught herself following the movement of his hand with her eyes involuntarily. He was just as well built as Hunter was, though a little taller and browner. Danny smirked at Hunter as Ella forced herself to drag her eyes away from Danny\'s chest. Hunter looked mildly annoyed.\r\n\r\nSay, Ella, ever spent the night in a camper van? Ella\'s shook her head. Danny grinned. Want to? Ella\'s mouth opened in shock. Danny poked his tongue out cheekily. Ella hit him playfully on his rock hard chest. Danny acted like Ella had really hurt him,